[[File:LBM-Lindsay.jpg|thumb|The Little Boy from Manly, drawn by [[Norman Lindsay]] during the [[Australian_plebiscite,_1916|1916 Conscription Referendum]]]] The '''Little Boy from Manly''' was a [[national personification]] of [[New South Wales]] and later [[Australia]] created by the [[cartoonist]] [[Livingston Hopkins]] of ''[[The Bulletin]]'' in April 1885.
In March 1885, as the [[New South Wales Contingent]] was about to depart for the [[Nile Expedition| Sudan]], a letter was addressed to Premier [[William Bede Dalley]] containing a cheque for £25 for the Patriotic Fund 'with my best wishes from a little boy at Manly'. It was Australia's first overseas military adventure, and the little boy became a symbol either of [[Australian patriotism]] or, among opponents of the adventure, of mindless [[chauvinism]]. Hopkins put the boy in a cartoon, dressed in the pantaloons and frilled shirt associated with English storybook schoolboys of the [[Namby Pamby|namby-pamby]] kind. Over the following decades, he became ''The Bulletin'''s stock symbol of Young Australia. <ref>Davison, Graeme, 'The Little Boy from Manly', in ''The Oxford Companion to Australian History'' (1998), p.395, {{ISBN|0 19 553597 9}}.</ref>
